;q=0.9,*/*;q=0.8", "Accept-Language": "en-us,en;q=0.5", "Sec-Fetch-Mode": "navigate"}, "format": "hls-akfire_interconnect_quic-1760 - 1920x1080"}, {"format_id": "hls-fastly_skyfire-1760", "format_index": null, "url": "https://skyfire.vimeocdn.com/1778070858-0xfad30ed1d8e63d3638fedeaa69eb6ec507607d91/73d7dde2-61d4-4c78-9f9d-e32fb97695a5/psid=b3e2e0681029eb4fa03e719540f6ea0ee7c9776b81b8990a11e220ee24835e90/v2/playlist/av/73d7dde2/avf/2f7c502a/media.m3u8?pathsig=8c953e4f~gEgadPPx3JcgyenfK9-DTcoMg_78O49HAWZyPn3RIdA&qsr=1&r=dXMtY2VudHJhbDE%3D&st=video", "manifest_url": "https://skyfire.vimeocdn.com/1778070858-0xfad30ed1d8e63d3638fedeaa69eb6ec507607d91/73d7dde2-61d4-4c78-9f9d-e32fb97695a5/psid=b3e2e0681029eb4fa03e719540f6ea0ee7c9776b81b8990a11e220ee24835e90/v2/playlist/av/primary/prot/cXNyPTE/playlist.m3u8?locale=en&omit=opus&pathsig=8c953e4f~ndEGBVdb6K6wz3dChcuRJhILFqc1ksXtRWsy4MG8M4k&qsr=1&r=dXM%3D&rh=RGn4O&sf=fmp4", "tbr": 1760.0, "ext": "mp4", "fps": 23.976, "protocol": "m3u8_native", "preference": null, "quality": null, "has_drm": false, "width": 1920, "height": 1080, "vcodec": "avc1.64002A", "acodec": "none", "dynamic_range": "SDR", "video_ext": "mp4", "audio_ext": "none", "abr": 0, "vbr": 1760.0, "resolution": "1920x1080", "aspect_ratio": 1.78, "http_headers": {"User-Agent": "Mozilla/5.0 (Windows NT 10.0; Win64; x64) AppleWebKit/537.36 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/141.0.0.0 Safari/537.36", "Accept": "text/html,application/xhtml+xml,application/xml;q=0.9,*/*;q=0.8", "Accept-Language": "en-us,en;q=0.5", "Sec-Fetch-Mode": "navigate"}, "format": "hls-fastly_skyfire-1760 - 1920x1080"}], "description": "2025 Academy Awards Shortlist: Best Animated Short Film\nPlease note, some scenes contain flashing lights that may affect photosensitive viewers.\n-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------\nsometimes when you make a movie, everything goes more or less according to plan, and, for better or worse, you get what you want and feel like maybe you know what you're doing. the \"world of tomorrow\" series is a good example of when things go surprisingly well. \nother times, a movie has to take the long way around. when i was making \"it's such a beautiful day\", the limitations of animating a feature-length story by myself with an old camera pushed everything further into the experimental wilderness than i thought i'd be going. i couldn't stage everything in a traditional way, so instead came up with a new sort of visual language: splitting up the screen and making everything more impressionistic. in those sorts of situations, you dive in without a map and try to feel your way through. if you can't do option A, then how can you make option B better?\nand still other times when you make a movie, the whole thing catches on fire and plummets down a flight of stairs. \"ME\" was one of those times.\na little over a year into production, all of the original music had to be cut from the film and i found myself in the strange position of having nearly completed a musical that suddenly no longer had any music in it. another year was needed to reanimate, recut, and reimagine the whole thing.\nand i'm not telling you this to make you feel sorry for the movie or suggest that it's compromised. on the contrary, the picture that's somehow still standing is leaner, more raw, and arguably stronger than it might have been had everything gone right. being born out of weird chaos gave the film an extra year of reflection, a new structure, and eventually a different sort of clarity. if you're forced to make changes, how can you turn changes into improvements? how can you make option B better?\n\"ME\" is therefore not a dog that's stumbling around missing a leg. it's a dog that now has wings. and i know dogs aren't supposed to have wings, but this dog does and somehow it works. they're dogwings, but they're still wings.\nthat's all to say, this is not what anyone expected it was going to be from day one and sometimes that's for the best. sometimes a movie has to take the really, really, really, long way around.\n\"ME\" is a story about narcissism. it's also a story about pain. \nit's also somehow still a musical. if you're watching on something that's not a tv, find a good set of headphones and don't be shy about the volume.\nit's really easy to worry about the future. it's really easy to worry about stuff that happened in the past. it can be hard sometimes to just be present. and before pressing play, i'd like to take a second to invite you to do whatever you might need to do to just be here now. close your eyes, take a breath, feel the weird weight of your body, turn off other distractions, whatever helps. it's just a good thing to try and remember from day to day. anyway, you're right here, it's right now, and this is something i made called \"ME\"\nthanks for watching \u2764\ndon\n-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------\n\"Enlightenment occurs when the usually automatized reflexivity of consciousness ceases, which is experienced as a letting-go and falling into the void and being wiped out of existence.\" - David Loy\n-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------\n\"One of the best animated films of the year... the type of movie that sticks with you long after it\u2019s finished, the type that makes you look at yourself, the people around you, and the world differently for having watched it.\" - Polygon\n\"A dialogue-free musical that pushes the animation extraordinaire\u2019s inventiveness to new heights. Starting as a small-scale family drama before reaching perhaps the widest scope of his work yet, it\u2019s a rhythmically captivating odyssey into the fabric of humanity.\" - The Film Stage\n\"A wordless dystopian animation that blends inter-dimensional compositions with the broken-puzzle poetry of 'Mulholland Drive'.\" - Sight and Sound\n\"A brilliant apocalyptic musical about narcissism... seems to explode from a cosmic collision between nothing and everything all at once... [Hertzfeldt's] films keep stretching toward the stars as they probe deeper into the pit of our souls.\" - Indiewire", "webpage_url": "https://vimeo.com/ondemand/marblehalls/1016625668", "id": "1016625668", "title": "ME", "uploader": "don hertzfeldt", "uploader_id": "donhertzfeldt", "uploader_url": "https://vimeo.com/donhertzfeldt", "thumbnails": [{"url": "https://i.vimeocdn.com/video/1934667067-f9dad986f54048b9202d53cadd37622f95037f7a9559629e5768595b4371d841-d", "id": "0"}], "duration": 44, "subtitles": {}, "timestamp": 1728184890, "width": 1920, "height": 1080, "original_url": "https://vimeo.com/ondemand/marblehalls/1016625668", "webpage_url_basename": "1016625668", "webpage_url_domain": "vimeo.com", "extractor": "vimeo:ondemand", "extractor_key": "VimeoOndemand", "playlist": null, "playlist_index": null, "thumbnail": "https://i.vimeocdn.com/video/1934667067-f9dad986f54048b9202d53cadd37622f95037f7a9559629e5768595b4371d841-d", "display_id": "1016625668", "fulltitle": "ME", "duration_string": "44", "upload_date": "20241006", "release_year": null, "requested_subtitles": null, "_has_drm": null, "epoch": 1778067241, "requested_downloads": [{"requested_formats": [{"format_id": "hls-fastly_skyfire-1760", "format_index": null, "url": "https://skyfire.vimeocdn.com/1778070858-0xfad30ed1d8e63d3638fedeaa69eb6ec507607d91/73d7dde2-61d4-4c78-9f9d-e32fb97695a5/psid=b3e2e0681029eb4fa03e719540f6ea0ee7c9776b81b8990a11e220ee24835e90/v2/playlist/av/73d7dde2/avf/2f7c502a/media.m3u8?pathsig=8c953e4f~gEgadPPx3JcgyenfK9-DTcoMg_78O49HAWZyPn3RIdA&qsr=1&r=dXMtY2VudHJhbDE%3D&st=video", "manifest_url": "https://skyfire.vimeocdn.com/1778070858-0xfad30ed1d8e63d3638fedeaa69eb6ec507607d91/73d7dde2-61d4-4c78-9f9d-e32fb97695a5/psid=b3e2e0681029eb4fa03e719540f6ea0ee7c9776b81b8990a11e220ee24835e90/v2/playlist/av/primary/prot/cXNyPTE/playlist.m3u8?locale=en&omit=opus&pat